40|$|Sorry, {{the full}} text of this article is not {{available}} in Huskie Commons. Please click on the alternative location to access it. 524 p. The dissertation compares the legal thought of four of the most active radical groups of the English Revolution [...] the Levellers, the Diggers, the Quakers, and the Fifth Monarchy Men. Analyzing the printed works of each group this study examines both legal theory and concrete criticisms and proposed reforms of the law. It attempts to show the relationship between each group's legal ideas and its political, social, and economic thought. In doing this, the dissertation reveals how law reform is also a good standard with which to measure more general similarities and differences within the mental worlds of the radicals. Many of the same reform demands appeared in the popular pamphlets and <b>collective</b> <b>statements</b> produced by each group. Yet, it is also demonstrated how different radicals took standard, accepted seventeenth-century legal and constitutional concepts and adapted them to their own needs and worldviews. By charting this creative adaptation, this dissertation touches upon broader themes concerning law and society in seventeenth-century England...|$|R
